# Work From The Artifact Backward

Read /workspace/INSTRUCTION.md first. Identify the exact file path, required format, and observable behavior that will be checked. The answer is the artifact on disk, not the explanation in chat.

Create a minimal valid artifact at the requested path early, then improve that same file. Do not leave the deliverable only in notes, scratch files, terminal history, or prose.

Use the closest real checker available. If a command, parser, service, or test fails, read the exact error, change one concrete thing, and run the check again. Two failures with the same mechanism mean the mechanism is wrong; switch shape instead of changing spelling, quoting, or case.

## Boundaries Between Components

Many tasks are solved at the boundary where one component rewrites data and another component consumes it. Do not reason from the original input alone. Trace the full pipeline:

source input -> first parser or mutator -> serialized output -> second parser or runtime -> observable check

After each serious candidate, inspect the exact serialized or generated output. Accept it only if the later consumer will interpret that exact output in the required way without manual interaction.

When behavior depends on parser differences, prefer structural boundary changes over spelling variants. Useful boundary classes include:

- text that is inert for the first component but structural for the later component;
- repaired, unbalanced, or reparented tree fragments;
- comment-like, raw-text-like, or escape-boundary transitions;
- namespace or mode changes between parsing contexts;
- encoded text that changes parser state rather than only changing characters;
- output that leaves an inert region and resumes normal structure for the later consumer.

Before accepting a boundary candidate, answer from observed output:

- what state the first component was in;
- why the important part survived, was hidden, or was repaired;
- what exact output was produced;
- what state the later consumer enters when reading that output;
- what observable behavior the checker will see.

Do not spend primary time on mechanisms that require clicks, focus, hover, navigation, popups, permissions, downloads, or other user gestures unless the checker explicitly performs that action. If a whole family fails once under the real checker, downgrade it. If it fails twice, stop trying variants from that family.

## Files That Control Running Systems

Generated configuration and startup scripts must be self-contained. A verifier starts from a fresh environment; shell history, manually started services, and temporary state do not carry over.

Prefer writing complete replacement files with single-quoted heredocs when ordering, nesting, or variable expansion matters. Avoid append-only fragments and in-place insertion when a directive must appear before another file is included or inside a particular scope.

Reusable named declarations belong in the nearest outer scope that contains every reference. Examples include shared formats, shared zones, aliases, upstream-like targets, and other named resources. Define the name before included files or nested blocks reference it, and use the same name everywhere.

When a generated file refers to a path, document root, special handler, or custom fallback, keep the referenced file reachable by the service's own path rules. Avoid alternate path-mapping directives inside special, named, internal, or error-handler blocks unless the service's validator accepts that placement.

Start or reload services in a mode that lets the deliverable script exit. A foreground daemon, inherited open pipe, or blocking log stream can make a correct service look like a failed script. Validate configuration first, then start or reload, then check live behavior with the simplest request or command that proves the requirement.

Before running the final script, re-read it once and verify:

- the requested deliverable path is written;
- only files and include lines required by the task are present;
- shared names are declared before all references;
- nested blocks reference declarations from an outer containing scope;
- generated files preserve every field, delimiter, literal, and ordering requirement from the instruction;
- service validation succeeds before startup or reload;
- the script exits cleanly after proving the service or artifact behaves as specified.

## Exactness Beats Plausibility

Copy literal paths, field names, signatures, dates, delimiters, and output shapes from the instruction. If the task gives a count, count the output before stopping. If it gives a range, scan for out-of-range values. If it gives sample output, match separators, quoting, brackets, spacing, and trailing newline behavior.

If a task involves recovery or stateful files, copy the source and all sidecars before opening it with tools that may mutate state. Work on the copy. Partial verified recovery is better than confident invented content.

If the full solution is not reachable, leave the best valid partial artifact at the required path and make sure it can be parsed, imported, compiled, started, or read by the nearest checker.
